{"cursor":"3488","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":":See [[ArtinâSchreier theorem]] for theory about [[real-closed field]]s.\n\nIn mathematics, 'ArtinâSchreier theory' is a branch of Galois theory, and more\nspecifically is a positive characteristic analogue of Kummer theory, for Galois\nextensions of degree equal to the characteristic p. introduced ArtinâSchreier\ntheory for extensions of prime degree p, and generalized it to extensions of\nprime power degree p n.\n\nIf K is a field of characteristic p, a prime number, any polynomial of the form\n\n: X^p - X + \\alpha,\\,\n\nfor \\alpha in K, is called an ArtinâSchreier polynomial. When\n\\alpha does not lie in the subset  \\{ y \\in K \\, | \\, y=x^p-\nx \\; \\mbox{for } x \\in K \\} , this polynomial is irreducible in K[X],\nand its splitting field over K is a cyclic extension of K of degree p. This\nfollows since for any root Î², the numbers Î² + i, for 1\\le i\\le p ,\nform all the rootsâby Fermat's little theoremâso the splitting field is \nK(\\beta) .\n\nConversely, any Galois extension of K of degree p equal to the characteristic of\nK is the splitting field of an ArtinâSchreier polynomial. This can be proved\nusing additive counterparts of the methods involved in Kummer theory, such as\nHilbert's theorem 90 and additive Galois cohomology. These extensions are called\nArtinâSchreier extensions.\n\nArtinâSchreier extensions play a role in the theory of solvability by radicals,\nin characteristic p, representing one of the possible classes of extensions in a\nsolvable chain.\n\nThey also play a part in the theory of abelian varieties and their isogenies. In\ncharacteristic p, an isogeny of degree p of abelian varieties must, for their\nfunction fields, give either an ArtinâSchreier extension or a purely inseparable\nextension.\n","linknr":131,"url":"Artin–Schreier_theory","recorded":1371241652,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Artin%E2%80%93Schreier_theory&action=edit","/w/index.